            <h2 id="what-a-newly-qualified-teacher-nqt-needs-to-learn">What a newly qualified teacher (NQT) needs to learn</h2>

            <p>There are 6 specific areas an NQT needs to learn and gain experience in.</p>

            <h3 id="motivating-pupils">
              <span class="number">1. </span> Motivating pupils</h3>
              <p>Pupils learn well when they feel inspired and motivated. NQTs need to use their teaching ability and skills to improve the wellbeing, motivation and behaviour of their pupils.</p>

              <h3 id="being-a-role-model">
                <span class="number">2. </span> Being a role model</h3>
                <p>Good role models can have a positive and long-lasting impact on pupil learning. NQTs should be great role models to their pupils - influencing their attitudes, values and behaviours.</p>

                <h3 id="challenging-pupils">
                  <span class="number">3. </span> Challenging pupils</h3>
                  <p>Pupil outcomes improve when they are given opportunities to develop their learning. NQTs need to set challenging goals for their pupils that will stretch their development.</p>

                  <h3 id="setting-expectations">
                    <span class="number">4. </span> Setting expectations</h3>
                    <p>Setting clear expectations can help pupils understand their learning environment.</p>

                    <p>NQTs need to ensure that pupils know the shared values of their school. Communicating these clearly will improve classroom and school culture.</p>

                    <h3 id="developing-supportive-relationships">
                      <span class="number">5. </span> Developing supportive relationships</h3>
                      <p>Supportive relationship with pupils can have a positive impact on their learning and success. NQTs should build a culture of mutual trust and respect in the classroom to support their pupils.</p>

                      <h3 id="high-quality-teaching">
                        <span class="number">6. </span> High-quality teaching</h3>
                        <p>Pupils’ life chances are dramatically improved by high-quality teaching. NQTs must offer a consistently high standard of teaching to have a long-term positive effect on pupils, especially children from disadvantaged backgrounds.</p>

                        <figure class="image embedded"><div class="img"><img src="https://assets.integration.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/image_data/file/89821/set2.png" alt="woman reading"></div></figure>

                        <h2 id="what-skills-an-nqt-needs-to-develop">What skills an NQT needs to develop</h2>

                        <p>To help NQTs succeed early on, mentors need to dedicate time to transferring their:</p>

                        <ul>
                          <li>valuable teaching experience</li>
                          <li>hands-on skills</li>
                          <li>leadership qualities</li>
                        </ul>

                        <p>A mentor needs to specifically help NQTs know how to:</p>

                        <ul>
                          <li>communicate a belief in the academic potential of all pupils</li>
                          <li>demonstrate consistently high behavioural expectations</li>
                        </ul>

                        <h3 id="skills-which-help-communicate-a-belief-in-the-academic-potential-of-all-pupils">Skills which help communicate a belief in the academic potential of all pupils</h3>

                        <p>An NQT needs to be able to:</p>

                        <ul>
                          <li>use intentional and consistent language to challenge and inspire</li>
                          <li>set achievable tasks that stretch pupils within a challenging curriculum</li>
                          <li>create a positive environment where making mistakes and learning from them is part of the daily routine</li>
                          <li>encourage effort and perseverance from all pupils</li>
                          <li>seek out opportunities to engage with parents and carers in the education of their children (for example, proactively highlighting successes)</li>
                        </ul>

                        <h3 id="skills-which-demonstrate-consistently-high-behavioural-expectations">Skills which demonstrate consistently high behavioural expectations</h3>

                        <p>An NQT needs to be able to:</p>

                        <ul>
                          <li>create a culture of trust and respect in the classroom that supports and helps all pupils to succeed (for example, model the types of courteous behaviour expected of pupils)</li>
                          <li>maintain and rigorously teach clear behavioural expectations (for example, class contribution, volume level and concentration)</li>
                          <li>apply rules, sanctions and rewards in line with school policy, escalating behaviour incidents as appropriate praise and acknowledge pupil effort and emphasis the progress made</li>
                        </ul>

                        <h2 id="resources">Resources</h2>

                        <p>Useful ideas and exercises you can use to train and support NQTs.</p>

                        <p><a href="/guidance/using-meditation-to-create-a-culture-of-respect-and-trust">Using meditation to create a culture of respect and trust</a></p>

                        <p><a href="/guidance/using-ground-rules-to-create-a-culture-of-respect-and-trust">Using ground rules to create a culture of respect and trust</a></p>
